- VSCode Version:  1.8.1
- OS Version: macOS 10.11.6

Steps to Reproduce:

In my theme I have: 

```xml
<key>selection</key>
<string>#ff0</string>
<key>selectionHighlight</key>
<string>#0f0</string>
<key>wordHighlight</key>
<string>#f00</string>
<key>wordHighlightStrong</key>
<string>#00f</string>
```

Test code:

```js
function test(source) {
	let parsedProps;
	try {
		parsedProps = propsParser(source);
	}
	catch (exception) {
		parsedProps = [];
	}
	return parsedProps;
}
```

1. Put cursor inside one of the `parsedProps` (looks fine so far):

![image 2017-01-04 at 11 13 53 am](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/70067/21639161/e4818ad6-d26e-11e6-9596-bfcf7c4e285c.png)

2. Select part of `parsedProps` (selected part has the same style as non-selected):

![image 2017-01-04 at 11 14 50 am](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/70067/21639188/088657cc-d26f-11e6-9b0d-c6717167594c.png)

What exist today is very limited, a one size fits all don't work for most people:

```
  "editor.tabSize": 4,
```

A suggested improvement:

```
  "editor.tabSize": {
     "default": 4,
     "web": 2,
     "cpp": 3
   }

   // Don't need to specify the '.' before extension name.
   // Specify multiple extensions with '|' or separator.
   tabFileExtensions: {
    "cpp": ['h|hpp|c|cpp|cc'],
    "web": ['js|html|css|ts']
   }
```

- VSCode Version: 1.8.0
Steps to Reproduce:
```ts
interface FooOption {
  /**
   * Doing boo stuff
   */
  boo(x: number): boolean
}

function foo(option: FooOption) {

}

foo({
  boo()
})
```
![image](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/3254987/21629779/2145d0a6-d1e0-11e6-965c-e674fe53d86d.png)

![image](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/3254987/21629764/08958916-d1e0-11e6-975a-87a74eb3f80c.png)

Currently, autocomplete is doing a better job than the tooltip. When you type `boo`, autocomplete gets the definition of `boo` and display it. But once you type `(`, it falls back to the tooltips and only show the tooltip of `foo(...)` instead. 

It would be nice to have the tooltips shows the info for `boo()`. 🌷
